snippet.textDisplay: His logic to justify his shooting and killing of 3 wolves doesn't make sense. He witnesses a rare event and decides to document it. He interjects himself into  a potentially bad situation and gets chased away by a massive pack of wolves. Wolves that are most likely protecting their kill. A kill they need to survive the winter. Since they didn't display typical wolf behavior (run away at first sight of man) he chose to put them in their place and kill three. He had a cabin to hide in. He chose to put himself into a situation he didn't fully understand then punishes the wolves because they didn't want him around? If he was in the woods, no cabin to run back to, and a pack of this size started exhibiting aggressive behavior then I'd understand him going on the offensive, but these animals were doing what wild animals do.

snippet.textDisplay:
9:32 "How do they know you're dangerous? Are they having any interactions with humans?"
Wolves have been hunted nearly into extinction by humans when we settled onto this land. The ones that have survived teach their young to fear humans. I don't believe that they evolved to fear us, I think that would take more time than has passed. I believe their fear is taught by the parent wolves to the young.
Wolves are apex predators so when a human comes around and an elder wolf says 'GTFO' they don't ask questions. Also they can smell us from a mile away so the adolescent wolves can quickly learn before even having seen a humans silhouette.

snippet.textDisplay: I think all pack animals that eat meat are dangerous in the right context. I've been confronted by packs of feral hogs that would've gladly torn me to pieces and devoured me if they could've gotten to me. Luckily I was up a really steep, large bank and they couldn't get up it to get to me. I've had live stock- goats mostly, and they killed my neighbor's foal- killed  by packs of coyote- and I read a story of some young lady killed by coyotes wile jogging up in Canada. Animals that are normally afraid of humans aren't nearly as afraid when in large packs.
